review_blob: bottle.  very dark, pours smooth and has a nice head that doesnt stick around.  definitely can taste the maltiness.  some spices and a hint of chocolate.  aroma is subtly spicy.

can.  the staple beer of la crosse wisconsin. pale yellow color, no head.  crisp and refreshing, though mine was served cold.  my older friends say that this is what old style used to taste like back in the 70s before heilemans went out of business.  for my money, better flavor than the flagship miller and budweiser products.

bottle.  pale yellow color with almost no head unless you pour the bottle directly down into the glass, then it just diminishes quickly.  strong hoppy flavor, though the aroma is unappetizing, smells of alcohol.
bottle.  hooray beer.  pours pale golden with a rapidly diminishing head.  i detect some fruity aroma and flavor, possibly banana, though it mainly tastes like a sweetened domestic american lager.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: bottle.  i guess i dont get the doppelbock in this one.  it seems more like a dark lager to me.  dark brown color, nice foamy head.  caramel and nuts and a hint of hops.
can. colored water.  not very flavorful.  acceptable aroma, color is pale yellow, and the taste is bitter.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: bottle.  not to get too nastolgic, but i think this beer tasted better before Miller bought them out.  flavor is the same, but the taste is a little week.  lots of caramel or something burnt in there.  beautiful color.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: bottle. not a fan. smelled very fruity and promising, but it was not very sweet to the taste.  i got a hit of some sort of berry mixture, but it was too conflicted with the hops and malt to stand out.

bottles (2).  ok flavor, though mine were quite bitter. i had a second one just to be sure, but i got the same impression.  gotta love anything danish, though the color and head are lousy.  didnt really care for the aroma either.

bottle. can really taste the corn in there, at least, thats what it reminds me of.  flavor seems just a bit off, too much of something strong on the back of my tongue, but i dont know how to describe it.
bottle.  loved the hoppy quality.  very fragrant, medium head.  i love this color as well.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: tap.  better than Miller or Budweiser by a long shot, but not all that great.  not enough character, either in the sweetness or aromatic categories, to warrant special attention.  Liked the hint of honey, liked that it poured a nice tall head.

tap. Too light to compete with my favorite brown ales.  I like the sweeter quality to it, though I wish it would have some more caramel or nuttiness to it.  Good in hot weather, which is unusual for a brown ale.
bottle.  a good economic choice for anyone outside of the midwest, but if you need to drink a dark lager, go with Leinenkugels Creamy Dark.
the stout to which all others of this class are compared...ive had it draft and from a can now...dont recommend the bottled version.  brilliant.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: bottle.  orangy-yellow with a nice head, which doesnt last very long.  very sweet and citrusy, almost like candy except beer...too sweet for my taste, sort of like a blue moon for diabetics or something like that.
bottle. nice color, amber...medium head.  piney and aromatic.  quite a good beer for the category and the price.

bottle.  pale gold, head seems to evaporate upon contact with oxygen... I like it better than Miller or Budweisers bottom-line beer.  Slightly bitter finish, small hoppiness, not much substance.  Very fizzy, another belching beer.  Affordable.  If you want to make friends in La Crosse I recommend buying them this one over the other domestics.

tap. one word: caramel.  A little burnt, and heavy like a Wisconsin, northwoods brown ale should be.  I can understand why they drink it year round up there.  Some taste of nuts, possibly chesnuts as the deScription indicates, and quite good on its own.  I had two, one with my beef pastie and another by itself, and both were good.  Widely available in WI, but I have trouble finding it elsewhere.  If you live where its cold half of the year, I dont know many brown ales that will be as affordable and that pair up as well as they stand alone.
beer_name: New Glarus Fat Squirrel Nut Brown Ale

review_blob: Bottle.  amber color, medium, longer lasting head.  I enjoyed the aroma of this one, and I have to say that the finish leaves my sweet-tooth wanting more.  In my opinion, far superior to domestic copies like Blue Moon.  Quite dry and clean.  It doesnt sit on the tongue, which I appreciated.

Tap.  Ive tried this in bottle, can, and on tap I still have to say that this beer tastes more like water to me than beer.  If you need something INCREDIBLY light with your dinner and you only have $5 in your wallet, okay, you can have this beer.  Its hard to rate things like flavor, aroma, etc. because I find them lacking.

Bottle.  Decent color for a massed produced import.  Light lager, with a bit of bitter in the finish.  I would say this is another refresher beer that is affordable to stock and I would definitely stock it en masse over most of the American macros.  Decent, affordable, light.

Bottle.  Very pale gold.  Cheap, easy to find, great for a light after-work relaxer.  Only complaint is that I was burping constantly while I drank this thing.  Too much carbonation without the flavor to back it up.

Bottle.  Nice and clear with a big head that doesnt last long.  Im not a fan of pilsner in general, but I thought that this beer was very good.  I find the after-taste a bit strong for my ale-indulged palate, but I think it tasted great with my heavier flavored burger.

12 oz. bottle.  Pale color.  This is beer has a lot of hoppy flavor, though not enough to make a statement.  I would say its one of the better pilsners you can buy in the states for a dollar a bottle.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: bottle.  This poured a very pretty amber color, not much of a head.  I dont think this beer tasted that much different from some of their other products, like honeyweiss.  It was a little bit too bitter for an "Oktoberfest" beer.  Slightly watery.

From tap, at Oktoberfest grounds in La Crosse.  A very nice reddish brown color.  The stuff smells pretty good.  It had a rather yeasty taste to it, and I think it could have used a little bit more flavor, for all of its good aroma.  I like the chocolate and molasses combination.

Bottle. I loved the color of this supposed witbier. It was a little darker than I expected.  I thought it was rather cosmetically appealing, for a Coors product.  Can definitely taste the bitterness of "orange peel," as the label says,  or whatever flavor they add to it to give it a little bit of bite.  Not bad for a beer you can buy at almost any Walmart.

16 oz can.  pours a pale yellow with a quickly disappearing head, not a lot of carbonation.  definitely a corn flavor to this beer.  watery with a hint of a bite to it.  i think it tastes better than its fuller brother.
